Date: Tue, 24 Oct 2000 23:41:49 -0400
From: Lam Sai Kit, Kenneth <lamsk@medicine.med.um.edu.my>

Hand, Foot And Mouth Disease In Malaysia - Update
-------------------------------------------------
A third enterovirus, Echovirus 7 (echo 7), has been identified during the
current outbreak of Hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD) in Malaysia. This
virus was isolated from a fatal case at the University Hospital Kuala Lumpur
(UHKL). The identification of this virus was conducted by Assoc. Prof. Dr.
Chua Kaw Bing, consultant virologist of UHKL, along with clinical virologist
Dr. Peter McMinn at the Princess Margaret Hospital, Perth.
Using VP4 RT-PCR and sequencing conducted at The Western Australian Centre
for Pathology and Medical Research (PATHCENTRE), Perth, the data generated
were sent to Dr. Hiroaki Ishiko, Infectious Diseases Department,
Mitsubishi-Kagaku Bio-Clinical Laboratories, Tokyo, Japan as he has an
extensive database of VP4 sequence from all 66 human enteroviruses. This
analysis provided an unequivocal match to Echovirus 7. Further confirmation
[was obtained by VP1 RT-PCR and sequencing revealing a close match to a
recent Spanish isolate (94% nucleotide sequence identity) and to the
prototype Wallace strain (89% nucleotide sequence identity).
Neutralization assays were conducted using RD cells and a complete set of
intersecting antiserum pools. This test confirmed the presumptive
identification of echo 7 made by VP4 and VP1 sequencing. A serum
neutralization assay on a convalescent serum from a 7-month old child showed
a high neutralizing titre (320) to isolate 15394 (echo 7) and no
cross-reactivity to the closely related echo 11 (<20). The convalescent
serum from a 5-year old child showed the phenomenon of "original antigenic
sin", with a neutralizing titre of 20 to echo 11 and <20 to the echo 7
virus isolate even though the virus was isolated from this child.
Echo 7 virus has been associated with several outbreaks involving central
nervous system disease. One such outbreak in Pondicherry, India, was
published in 1969 where there were 26 cases of encephalitis with several
deaths. In Sweden in 1973, an outbreak of meningoencephalitis due to echo 7
and Coxsackie B3 was reported and echo 7 was isolated from 19 patients.
There was no fatality during this outbreak.
During the present hand, foot and mouth outbreak, several enteroviruses
have been isolated by UHKL. These included 7 Coxsackie A16, 14 enterovirus
71, one Coxsackie B, 12 herpes simplex and 6 echo 7. However, 5 of the 6
echo 7 virus isolates were from severe and fatal encephalitis. The
identification of echo 7 in severe and fatal cases during an outbreak of
HFMD in Malaysia is of global interest because of the increase in emerging
and re-emerging diseases worldwide.
--
Lam Sai Kit, Kenneth
<lamsk@medicine.med.um.edu.my>
[ProMed-mail is indebted to Professor Lam for this informed and lucid
account of the virological background to the current outbreak of HFMD in
Malaysia. This is how it should be done. - Mod.CP

