From: Dr Muruga Vadivale <vale@pop.jaring.my>
Source: New Straits Times, filed Mon 24 Oct 2000 [edited
<http://www.geocities.com/vadivale>

Hand, Foot & Mouth Disease in Malaysia & Singapore: Virological Findings
------------------------------------
KUALA LUMPUR: On Mon 24 Oct 2000 [it was announced that a virulent
enterovirus never detected before locally had killed [more accurately "been
isolated from" - Mod.CP a child who contracted hand, foot and mouth disease
(HFMD) recently and may have been responsible for the death of 3 others. Dr
Peter McMimm of the Princess Margaret Hospital for Children in Perth,
Australia, confirmed this today after extensive tests in the past 7 days.
Speaking to the New Straits Times in a telephone interview, Dr McMimm said
he was leaving it to the Health Ministry here to reveal the name of the
enterovirus [now identified as Echovirus type 7 in Professor Lam's statement
above - Mod.CP. He said only one of the samples brought to Perth by Dr Chua
of the University Hospital Kuala Lumpur had yielded positive results, [but
the presence of Enterovirus 71 could be excluded.
He added that the precautionary measures carried out by health authorities
in Malaysia were sufficient to contain the disease. Considering that the
number of cases have been declining, the measures taken have been effective.
"This virus [subsequently revealed to be Echovirus type 7, while not
new, is one of the less common strains. Although never before detected in
Malaysia, it has shown up in other parts of the world."
Meanwhile, findings by Singapore's Ministries of Environment; Health;
Community Development and Sports; and Education, released here today said it
was "strongly believed" that Enterovirus 71 (EV71) was the main cause of the
HFMD outbreak in the Republic, although other enteroviruses have also been
isolated. Dr Ling Ai Ee and Dr Chan Kwai Peng, of Singapore General
Hospital's Department Of Pathology, identified EV71 in samples from 2
children who died in the republic on 30 Sep 2000. Their findings [had been
confirmed by the United States' Centers for Disease Control. The
Singaporean virologists also found EV71 present in the samples of surviving
siblings of the 2 children. No virus, however, had been identified in
another child who died on 10 Sep 2000. According to the statement, completed
virological studies showed that 80 per cent of the samples from fatal and
hospitalised cases and contacts had grown enteroviruses, [and EV71 had been
confirmed in almost half of the positive samples. The National University
of Singapore, together with the Virology Laboratory at the General Hospital,
had also found that the sequences of viruses for the fatal cases were
closely related to the EV71 strain associated with the outbreak in the
region in 1997. The statement also said that the number of HFMD cases in
Singapore was declining.
[Byline: Chok Suat Ling
--
Dr Muruga Vadivale
<vale@pop.jaring.my>
[The question arises whether the fatalities observed in these epidemics of
what is normally a mild disease are determined by infection by a single
enterovirus or a combination of agents. - Mod.CP
